<kml>

<concept name=Impair><system-documentation name=Impair>
<superconcept name=Action>

<definition>
  Impair an object so it becomes worse or less effective.
</definition>

<requiredslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=object>
     The object that's impaired.
  </slotdescription>

</requiredslotlist>

<primaryslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=agent>
    the entity that caused the impair to occur.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=instrument>
    the thing that was used to impair the object.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=by-means-of>
    the event that caused the impair to occur.
  </slotdescription>

</primaryslotlist>

<examplesentencelist>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>The fog impaired Billy's vision.</text>
    <slotdescription name=agent>The Fog</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=object>Billy's vision</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>
  <comment>
     Billy's vision becomes less effective. Billy's vision, however, 
     is not damaged. If its damaged, then use <conceptref name=Damage> 
     to describe the action.
  </comment>

</examplesentencelist>

<neighborlist>

  <neighbor name=Damage>
     A damage is a special kind of impair in which the object is not a living thing.
  </neighbor>
  
  <neighbor name=Harm>
     A harm is a special kind of impair in which the object is a living thing. 
  </neighbor>

</neighborlist>

</kml>


